messages.text: What are you having?
A vegan omelet please.
Oh. You‚Äôre one of those.
I suppose you also want organic beet juice squeezed by organic Greek virgins?
That sounds delicious, but I think I‚Äôll have a vanilla milkshake instead.
There‚Äôs hope for you yet, honey.
A man in the booth beside Taylor‚Äôs turns around as the waitress leaves.
Dark hair spills from the man‚Äôs Mohawk as he peels away the hood from his jacket.
Taylor‚Äôs heart thumps wildly in her chest when she sees the face she knows so well.
You know she‚Äôs going to slip clubbed baby seal meat in that omelet, right?
Taylor looks down, unable to calm her escalating heartrate.
What are you doing here?
Jonathan stands, dropping a few bills on the table.
Just finished eating. Can I join you?
At her small nod, Jonathan slides into the seat opposite Taylor.
How are you?
I‚Äôm okay.
Are you back to teaching?
No. I can‚Äôt be around kids‚Ä¶
Sorry.
Don‚Äôt be. Just feel what you need to feel.
I‚Äôve already done that enough.
At least, that‚Äôs what I keep telling myself.
You need more time.
There‚Äôs nothing wrong with that.
Time doesn‚Äôt seem like enough.
Then maybe you just need a friend.
Jonathan, please don‚Äôt.
I‚Äôm sorry.
I‚Äôve been trying to give you space.
But my life‚Äôs not the same without you.
I know.
I miss you.
I miss you, too.
So, what now?
I don‚Äôt know.
I guess I have to figure things out.
Alone?
For the time being, yes.
I don‚Äôt like the idea of you being alone.
You, me, and Blake‚Ä¶we‚Äôve always had each other.
I know, but‚Ä¶
Yeah. I get it.
Me and Blake‚Ä¶we‚Äôre trying to be friends. We even went to a football game on Sunday.
Did you hate it?
Every freaking minute.
Taylor laughs.
Blake told me that you looked positively miserable.
But that you hung in there.
You saw him?
Yes. We met for drinks.
We try to get together when we can.
He didn‚Äôt mention that.
We talk a lot, but he never says anything about you.
He should. We‚Äôre trying our best to be friends.
Just friends?
That‚Äôs all we can ever be now, Jonathan.
The waitress drops off the omelet and milkshake.
Taylor thanks her but doesn‚Äôt do more than stare at her plate.
What are you doing with yourself?
What do you mean?
How are you spending your days?
I‚Äôve been writing music, poems‚Ä¶things like that.
How‚Äôs that going?
Some days, it‚Äôs good. Others, not so much.
I‚Äôm spending most of my time volunteering.
Where?
At the retirement community. I play piano there.
They were looking for someone to direct their musical, so I told them I‚Äôd do it.
Let me guess, Cats?
No.
Little Shop of Dentures?
No.
Hair-less?
They both laugh.
If you must know, it‚Äôs Hello Dolly.
Isn‚Äôt that the one with all those dance numbers?
That‚Äôs right.
Aren‚Äôt you scared someone will break a hip?
Taylor makes a face.
Yes, but I‚Äôm not telling them that.
A few minutes pass.
It‚Äôs great to see you, Tay.
It‚Äôs been a long time.
What are your talking about?
You‚Äôve seen me all over town.
At the pub the other night‚Ä¶
And in the park last week.
I know.
I was starting to think you were following me.
No, just trying to do my thing.
But‚Ä¶damn it, Tay, it‚Äôs just not the same.
I want to be with you.
Like we were, before?
No, not like before.
Taylor‚Äôs eyes sting with tears. She stands, clutching her purse.
I can‚Äôt do this.
I can‚Äôt pretend nothing happened when everything did.
Jonathan wraps his strong arms around Taylor when she starts to cry.
He kisses her forehead lightly.
Tay, I wish I knew what to say or do.
I screwed up in the worst way.
Your pain ‚Äî and Blake‚Äôs ‚Äî I feel it down in my soul.
This isn‚Äôt all your fault.
Yes, it is.
If it weren‚Äôt for me telling you how I felt, you wouldn‚Äôt have been so stressed.
If I hadn‚Äôt interrupted your wedding, you wouldn‚Äôt have run.
I don‚Äôt know. Maybe I would have.
I don‚Äôt believe it.
Had I kept quiet, you and Blake would be married.
You‚Äôd be dreaming of holding your baby.
Tears pool in Taylor‚Äôs light blue eyes as she steps away from Jonathan‚Äôs embrace.
I know you need me to be something more.
But I can‚Äôt be.
It hurts too much to see you.
And it hurts not to love you like I want to.
Minutes stretch between them.
I don‚Äôt think we should talk anymore.
Please, Taylor.
Don‚Äôt push me away.
I don‚Äôt have a choice.
Every time I see you, you remind me of everything that went wrong.
I‚Äôm sorry.
I wish there were better words than that‚Ä¶
But sorry is all I have.
I forgive you.
But I can‚Äôt forgive myself.
I love you, Jonathan.
Goodbye.
Taylor starts to walk away.
She makes it to the door when the sound of Jonathan‚Äôs voice stops her.
I‚Äôll always be here for you, Taylor.
And I swear to God, I‚Äôll never stop loving you.
